(40, 1, '2018-03-16 00:46:59', '2018-03-16 04:46:59', 'I have always enjoyed making films that touch on the social aspect of what is happening right now in our society. It is always a commentary on how ludicrous or how weird everything is starting to become. What used to be uncanny and unacceptable, at least 10 or 20 years ago, is the “new normal”. In my film Donor (2010), the act of selling one’s organ for 100,000 pesos that is a part of you, your identity, and who you are is just \"normal”.  I always begin the concepts of my film by looking and exploring around unusual jobs. It actually started when I read about a job called “organ transporter”, which is actually a legal job. This is a job that is being practiced in the United States and Mexico.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-42\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture11-1024x682.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"840\" height=\"559\" />\r\n\r\nThe responsibility of this person is to transport organs for emergency and operations. Do you imagine the moral issues that you deal with moving organs? When I started writing the script and doing research, I have studied that the Philippines is the third country in the whole world with the biggest issue of \"organ trafficking” — First is China, second is India, and third comes the Philippines. I thought it was shocking that many people in the Philippines are selling their organs for a price. When i started telling and sharing to people what about my research and idea for the film, I spoke to Joel Lamangan and he said “Go to Baseco. There are a lot of people there who have sold their organs” and I asked him “Paano ko malalaman? You don’t just go there.” and Joel replied “No, no. just go there”, and so I did. I went to Baseco and looked for the barangay captain. True enough I told the barangay captain that i needed to interview someone who has sold their kidney for a fee and he told me, “Madali lang yan. Halika, sumama ka sa akin” . We went to the Gawad Kalinga village in Baseco, he knocked on the first door and surprisingly the person who happened to live there already sold his kidney. Imagine how many people who reside in Baseco has sold their kidneys for a price. Apparently 90% of the pedicab drivers in Baseco have sold a kidney 7 or 8 years ago.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-43\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture12-1024x682.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"840\" height=\"559\" />\r\n\r\nEach one of them has different prices and varying stories. The sad thing is after the operation has been conducted, they have sold what they think is a huge amount of money costing 100,000 pesos. They were caught off guard. After a year, the 100,000 pesos was already spent. They did not have anything to show. They think that their lives will be normal but it wouldn\'t for the reason that they are more prone to sickness like high blood pressure and they are more susceptible to diseases because they lost an organ in their system. At the same time, smoking and drinking is prohibited to people who have donated their kidneys because their resistance is weaker compared to when they still had both. It is like we do not know what is \"normal\" anymore.', 'What is Normal?: Organ Trafficking in the Philippines', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-is-normal-organ-trafficking-in-the-philippines', '', '', '2018-03-16 02:34:43', '2018-03-16 06:34:43', '', 0, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/?p=40', 0, 'post', '', 0),
