red by the Producer and being hurried to finish immediately (the Producer was right there, behind the camera).</li>\r\n 	<li>YOUTH-ORIENTED FILMS HAVE A STRONG AND CONSIDERABLE MARKET IN CINEMALAYA. Students all over the country have become true fans of the two leads and the film. Fortunately, the leads deliver engaging and heartfelt performances, have strong chemistry together and are both easy on the eyes. And the film turned out to be a real delight: by turns humorous, dramatic, romantic and simply charming. Which brings me to:</li>\r\n 	<li>A CROWD-PLEASING CINEMALAYA FILM IS A JOY TO BE PART OF. As in any festival, it’s a great feeling being part of an audience that gets caught up in the story you are telling. And since the festival runs for sometime, you become part of a movie-going community that shares your pride in your work… just as you become part of the other actors’ and companies’ journey.</li>\r\n 	<li>INDUSTRY VETERANS AND CO-WORKERS WILL BE THE FIRST TO SHOW THEIR APPRECIATION FOR YOUR WORK. Hit filmmaker Direk Joey Javier Reyes enthused, “THIS should be the kind of film that Star Cinema is producing!” when I saw him right after our screening. He said the film was so fresh and just lovely. Actor and director Rowell Santiago saw it at a later time but made sure to call on the phone just to say he liked the film very much. Such generous comments from respected professionals are, to say the least, heart-warming.</li>\r\n 	<li>FOOD IS STILL THE CHOICE OF BONDING ACTIVITY – ON ANY SET. Sharing hearty meals will always draw a family closer together, and this is very true on the set, where you are also sharing a vision, the challenges and the exhilaration of completing every scene together.</li>\r\n 	<li>AND THE TALENT FEE IS THE LAST THING YOU THINK OF WHEN YOU ARE ENJOYING DOING A PROJECT. This is the BS-free truth.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nA recent viewing of some clips in this nine year old film made me realize how its charm holds up to this day. It’s still a story worth watching, and a movie with its heart in the right place.\r\n\r\nAnd making it was a truly delightful Cinemalaya experience.', 'Acting for Cinemalaya Made Me Realize...', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '66-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-16 01:09:38', '2018-03-16 05:09:38', '', 66, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/2018/03/16/66-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(70, 1, '2018-03-16 01:12:39', '2018-03-16 05:12:39', 'I’ve supported Cinemalaya for about 7 yrs now, and I’ve seen a drastic change on concepts.\r\n\r\nIn the past years, Cinemalaya offered a platform for talented independent filmmakers however progressed to a space for art. For us Filipinos, family is where we’ll always have a soft spot for and from 2008, the storylines has always been limited - rather reserved. Cinemalaya through the years have escalated to be the landscape of family, politics, sex, drugs, religion and I would say filmmakers started playing around the storylines of these issues in 2012, at least for me when I started seeing the “abstract”. I came across this indie film called “Ang Nawawala” by Marie Jamora and if anyone would have take a look on their poster it would look like a movie for hipsters. Is it about family?<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-72\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture21.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"337\" />\r\n\r\nYes. Is there drama? Yes. Romance? Yes. Everyone looks for “not so brilliant but maybe new” “yung bago naman, puro ganun naman storya eh boy meets girl ends up or doesn’t end up together one dies or one has cancer and survives then becomes a family person”  YES THIS IS EXACTLY THE FRONT OF “Ang Nawawala”. What I liked about it is the story played along the lines of “yes we are predictable” and “nope that’s not what I expected”. The story is about a boy who saw his twin die in front of his eyes. The boy comes back home from abroad to a dysfunctional family. The boy finds himself wanting to fix his family by talking/ consulting to his dead twin.  He highlights the silences that do exist in long drawn bouts with grief.\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-73\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture22.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"957\" height=\"535\" />\r\n\r\nThe story shows the complexity of a family that goes through a circumstance and how they can get out of it - how they help themselves. Gibson (the main character in the story), is the main focus of the story.  Yes the film gave out romantic cliches and how a normal teenager should act but this is my personal ideal storyline for family concept. The story shows the characters going through emotional hardship, to a point where each of them gave up their dreams. One day, the dad of Gibson sneaks inside his room and find his computer open with thumbnails of videos. If I didn’t mention, Gibson walks around with a camera in the story - that’s why perception from viewers of the film is that it could be hipster. Anyway, to cut the chase the dad opens the videos and they were all moments of joy, joy that is something to cry a waterfall about - literally. The scene cuts to Gibson behind his camera taking those moments and he closes his eyes to feel it. This is for me the perfect rendition (OUT OF ANYTHING ELSE IN FAMILIAL MOVIES) of HURT in the family is - losing someone and could not get out the circumstance.  This boy keeps beautiful moments with him, hoping for change in his family. At the end, it did not have that big family hug playing “seasons of love in the background” NO!. RATHER, the ending is remarkable. The director ended it with just the mom and Gibson - no dad, and two sisters in the frame. They were all busy in outside watching the fireworks, and Gibson goes inside the room of his mom. While his mom is sleeping he picks her up on his lap, watching TV of New year coverage on the screen. Gibson closes his eyes, without his camera and speaks.\r\n\r\nFamily-oriented films are notorious for “not bagging the award” because obviously in watching a slice of life kind of films production does not concentrate on visuals, editing and other technical stuff unless it is like the concept of “Ang Nawawala”. The impact of these films for a viewer’s standpoint is something they would rather brew at the back of their heads after watching, or something they just forget. Family-oriented films become impactful (at least for me personally) if 1) there’s a twist 2)they don’t end up singing and hugging in front of a grand piano at the end 3) a dash of humor. Filipinos are known for being very festive, creative and looking for a film that fits them (not only referring to family oriented movies but the diversity of movie genres as well) however, at ending credits of every film that we watch, no matter how much twist and turns (abstract, creativity, complexity of production) , upside downs,  family is a place that is our home for Filipinos and it is a concept we all yearn to see.', 'Cinemalaya Feels Like Home', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cinemalaya-feels-like-home', '', '', '2018-03-16 02:33:20', '2018-03-16 06:33:20', '', 0, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/?p=70', 0, 'post', '', 0),
